    <methods>
      <methodStep>
        <description>
          <section>
            <title>Measure of thaw depth using metal thaw probe and organic layer depth by visual observation</title>
            <para>Thaw depth was measured using a metal thaw probe, which was inserted into the soil until there was resistance from frozen ground. Thaw depth is reported as the distance from the moss surface to top of frozen ground. Organic layer depth was measured by cutting into the soil with serrated knife and measuring the distance from the bottom of green moss layer to the organic-mineral boundary, as determined by visual observation.</para>
          </section>
        </description>
      </methodStep>
      <sampling>
        <studyExtent>
          <description>
            <para>Data were collected from Alaska permafrost borehole sites in July and August of 2015.</para>
          </description>
        </studyExtent>
        <samplingDescription>
          <para>At each site, we established three 20 meter long transects that were spaced 20 m apart and located adjacent to the permafrost boreholes. Thaw depth was measured every meter along the transect, and organic layer depth measured every five meters.</para>
        </samplingDescription>
      </sampling>
    </methods>
